Windows User Account Management & Access Control Lab
Overview

This lab demonstrates hands-on experience with Windows user account management, focusing on access control, account lifecycle management, and basic security administration. The goal was to simulate real-world system administration tasks aligned with enterprise cybersecurity and compliance environments.

Skills Demonstrated

Local user account creation and deletion

Account renaming and modification

Password protection and account security

User Account Control (UAC) awareness

Role separation between administrator and standard users

Access control principles (least privilege)

Technical Actions Performed

Created multiple local user accounts through Windows Control Panel

Configured password-protected accounts

Renamed existing user accounts

Deleted user accounts with and without preserving user files

Reviewed and interacted with User Account Control (UAC) prompts

Verified account status and permissions via Manage Accounts

Security Concepts Applied

Access Control (NIST 800-53 AC family)

Least Privilege

Account Lifecycle Management

User Authentication & Authorization

Relevance to Enterprise & Federal Environments

These tasks align with common responsibilities in system administration and cybersecurity roles, including:

Managing user access

Supporting incident containment (disabling/removing accounts)

Maintaining secure system configurations

Supporting compliance frameworks such as RMF

Tools & Environment

Windows 10 / 11

Control Panel

Local User Accounts

User Account Control (UAC)

